<article  data-comment-user-id="0" id="comment-133029" class="comment comment--level-1 by-anonymous" role="article" data-drupal-selector="comment">
  <div class="comment__text-wrapper">
    <footer class="comment__meta">
      <p class="comment__author"><span>Will (not verified)</span></p>
      <p class="comment__time">1 year 3 months ago</p>
                </footer>
    <div class="comment__content">
      
            <div class="text-content field field--name-comment-body field--type-text-long field--label-hidden field__item comment__text-content"><p>Been planting and harvesting carrots for decades. One of my fav's. I plant the Danvers variety, the soil isn't as much of an issue. I till and sift as best as I can and plant. When they start coming up, I use grass clippings between the rows and gently drop dry clippings over and around the carrots. I do enjoy a warm June day to thin and weed carrots. Its a bit of a task but I actually look forward to dropping all my cares and bask in the sun. I harvest sparingly to thin some out. In November, just as the ground here in S. NH is beginning to freeze, I fill large plastic trash bags full of leaves and place them right over the rows, covering as much of the crop as I can. This is a great insulator, push the snow aside and I have carrots until March. The ground under the leaves is soft and carrots come out easily. Works great for parsnips too. Problem is there is now more snow to remove!</p>
</div>
      <ul class="links inline comment__links">
          <li class="comment__links-item"><a href="/comment/reply/node/90062/comment_node_plant/133029" class="comment__links-link">Reply</a></li>
      </ul>
